This may seem odd, and I've probably got some dissociation going on that I should discuss more with my therapist, but one of the skills we're working on is radical acceptance. I am where I am at any given moment and that's okay.

And sure, in a lot of ways, I'm right. I will, in fact, have some "bad" days again. I won't lie to myself about the reality of my mental health.

But I can also remind myself that on the good days, I'm still me. I'm really actually doing the things I do.

I just realized that on some level I consider productive days less *real* than depressed days. This is temporary, I tell myself, when I'm having a "good" day. It won't last. I'm not really actually this competent.

Self-care isn't a depression solution for me. I feel worse when I think "I should really wash my hair today" and then still can't manage it. But what I can do is put self-care first when I am able to get up and do a thing. Because I'm worth prioritizing.

I've been really depressed lately, and today I'm feeling a tiny bit better. I'm way behind on work.

But instead of immediately doing that, I'm going to wash my hair for the first time in a while and do a face mask. And then I'll clean up the kitchen and eat a decent meal.

I am of the opinion that the typical "self-care" shit people talk about - take a bath! pamper yourself! exercise! - is not particularly helpful for ADHDers to hear. Sure, I'd love to. EXCEPT MY BRAIN WON'T LET ME GET OFF THE COUCH EVRN THOUGH I'M ANTSY BORED TO DEATH.

Many people are feeling trapped right now. I've been feeling that way for a while, and I don't wish it on anyone.

Coronavirus isolation is definitely not helping. I was occasionally able to escape - to go out for the day and hang out with my parents and brother, or work at a coffee shop. Being in a play last summer was so good for my mental well-being.
That is where I am now, and have been since last January. It is very hard. My executive functioning is worse than ever. I'm eating very poorly so I'm getting more migraines.

And when those little wounds are coming at you all at once and all the time from the environment that you are supposed to call home, where you are supposed to be able to go to help yourself heal from the wounds caused by the world, well.

But when the mental stress is the overwhelm of losing a job and trying to build some kind of business out of freelance work that no one wants to pay decently for and you have to move and store half your stuff away, those little wounds don't heal very easily.

I can deal with stressors like smells, noises, the feel of things on my skin, humidity, bugs, and such well enough normally. They make a little wound but it scabs and heals. The wound is worse if I'm also dealing with mental and emotional stress, but still, I can manage.

I feel like I have no skin. When you get a small wound, a scab forms as the new skin grows back, and when it is ready, the scab falls off. If the scab comes off too soon, the new skin is tender and easily reinjured, or isn't there at all yet and the bleeding starts again.

But they're just a group of people liking a thing. And guess what? You, theoretical award hater, are also a person who presumably likes some things. So like what you like, and maybe try not hating that other people like stuff too, possibly with different criteria than your own.
Awards are great! They help creators get recognition and help consumers find new stuff. I often use award lists as starting points for discovery. Not hating on their existence here.

The newness of the @theATTAs highlights this in a way that may make people who place a lot of value on certain awards feel uncomfortable. Even their favorite long-standing award is just a thing that's made up by a group of people.

They are not magic. There is no such thing as a universal objective measure of quality that an award can assess or bestow.

An award is literally just a bunch of people saying "hey, we think this thing is pretty great! maybe check it out if you want."

I love the existence of the @theATTAs but if people are upset by it (not on my timeline, so I'm following the right people), I have a theory beyond "I am scared of diversity" (which is definitely a part of it).

Awards are *always* just decided by a group of people.
